@inquisitorwalmarius6650 I understand that. I‚Äôm also poor, indebted, and work low-income, manually intensive jobs. I think the first correlates to the former though‚Äî the extreme decadence being a symptom of deprivation, or vice versa, or *both* being connected to some other root cause?

Both are problems that need solving though. Implementing more responsible frameworks for investors to abide, constraining the breadth of their investment across useless start-up projects, maybe? It might reduce the number of these overpaid, bonus-laden nonsense roles which exist. Taxing the companies for failed start-ups? Continuing to shame this extravagant decadence and offering small subsidies to those projects which forward productive and useful ideas and results? We still have the problem of defining ‚Äòproductive‚Äô and ‚Äòuseful‚Äô, since who‚Äôs to determine that and how do we know their definitions are better than ours, but it might encourage investment to be more focussed and *invested*, and less passive or ‚Äòlaissez-faire‚Äô. Can we find extra-occupational projects for these young high-flyers to engage in which stimulates their creativity/productivity at work while ‚Äúbearing it true‚Äù according to the needs of the city, nation, and world?

I don‚Äôt know what to do about underemployment or stagnant wages I‚Äôm afraid, since at least the latter seems to be almost insoluble: a symptom of oversaturated markets with enormous companies competing for limited resources, straining the amount of ‚Äúvalue added‚Äù by its employees, per unit of employment, and thereby reducing the amount of money they can be compensated for their wage-labour. I hate to sound conservative but it might very well be a case of find more meaningful work in a higher paying, less saturated market; hunker down, be diligent and aim for promotion; or, simply suck it up and do nothing, because there isn‚Äôt really anything that *can* be done *for* someone in that position.

@inquisitorwalmarius6650 Are these orgies the symptom of pre-fall decadence? Or are they the symptom of psychological schizophrenia expressing at the periphery of social organisation after its limited cultural (sexual) energy has burned up, for want of its more appropriate and natural outlet‚Äî sex? And might this indicate that just as we live ‚Äúin the shadow of Freud‚Äù, that so too did our ancestors, as in they relied *only* on their sexual energy to motivate them culturally, when in fact a *human* is much more than their procreative instinct, impulse, urge? 

Perhaps then this cyclic pattern is as much an expression of defective, maybe *partial* (or ‚Äòfractal‚Äô) psychology, as it is some necessary rule that sexual energy alone might fuel our projects, only to be inevitably inappropriately channeled by some civilisation‚Äôs later-stage citizens until hedonism prevails and society collapses? 

Perhaps the tension between primal instinct and generative creativity was a tension born of a false dichotomy, but one conveniently designed to manufacture a condition of constant revolution by design? So, who then might have designed that tension and why? Who stands to gain from this? And how might we resolve this tension if it in fact exists, and is in fact a problem?

